<section class="w-section">
  <div class="w-inner">
    <p class="w-eyebrow reveal"><span class="w-glyph" aria-hidden="true">▲</span> The Problem</p>
    <h2 class="w-h2 reveal" data-stagger="2">Public data is free. The engineering&nbsp;isn't.</h2>

    <div class="w-pain-grid">
      <div class="w-pain-block reveal">
        <h3>The pipeline is the&nbsp;project.</h3>
        <p>Market prices in one API, weather and climate in others. Satellite in NetCDF, forecasts in GRIB. Binary formats built for scientists, not traders. Months of engineering before a single&nbsp;trade.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-pain-block reveal" data-stagger="2">
        <h3>Four units, one&nbsp;reading.</h3>
        <p>ASOS sensors record in Fahrenheit. Live APIs serve Celsius. Historical archives round to tenths of Celsius. Satellite is in Kelvin. Four units per reading to&nbsp;reconcile.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-pain-block reveal" data-stagger="3">
        <h3>Platforms settle&nbsp;differently.</h3>
        <p>Kalshi's NYC high-temp settles on Central Park ASOS. Polymarket settles on Wunderground LaGuardia. Same city, different data. Every new market is days of&nbsp;research.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <blockquote class="w-callout reveal" data-stagger="4">
      <p>NOAA gives you the satellite data for free. Reading it correctly is the part that costs you weeks. 3.7 million NetCDF files across two GOES satellites, a new scan every five minutes. We handle the projection, dedup, and validation. You get a clean&nbsp;number.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
